  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">ECHO 2019</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1) Target villages, TP households, IDPs and host households, 2) Support the establishment or revitalization of complaints committees, 3) Establish a transfer mechanism for beneficiary households, 4) Monitor project implementation, 5) Implement the context and price monitoring system, 6) Target children 6-23 months and EFAFs, 7) Ensure regular screening of children aged 6-59 months and referrals of children with PB &lt; 125 mm, 8) Raising awareness and training of mothers on flour preparation and storage techniques and good practices in infant and young child feeding, 9) Acquiring and ensuring the distribution of enriched infant flour to targeted children 6-23 months, 10) Acquiring and distributing White Water to FEFA, 11) Conduct 2 Post Distribution Monitoring (PDM) surveys on flour, baseline and endline distributions, 12) Participate and facilitate coordination meetings at local and national level, 13) Support the holding of a capitalisation workshop, 14) develop an advocacy strategy to accelerate the implementation of the National Register</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">the action will enable households to have the necessary resources to ensure their food intake, to have the energy and time to work in their own fields - anything that will improve their food supply. In addition, it will enable beneficiaries to protect or restore their livelihoods. The nutritional approach, through awareness-raising and training, the involvement of all socio-economic groups, the production and use of porridges based on local products, guarantees the development and normal growth of children and allows FEFA to supplement their food needs.</narrative>
  </description>
